More than 60 per cent of Garissa families need relief food but the state is only catering for only 40 per cent of them, the county National Drought Management Authority official has said.NDMA county coordinator Abdi Noor said he is liaising with the Devolution and Planning departments to provide food aid to the growing list of vulnerable families, hurt by the prolonged drought.He spoke to the press in Garissa town on Tuesday during the flagging off of livestock feeds to Garissa Township. The NDMA said the worst-hit areas are Balambala, Ijara, Hulugho, Lagdera, Dadaab, Fafi and Garissa Township.County commissioner James Kianda said he has instructed all deputy county commissioners to liaise with subcounty education directors to ensure that every school gets its share of relief food.